Volunteer Shout Out

Woot! Woot! Just wanted to give a major shoutout to Evan Ridley, Steve Willis and our amazing CEC for helping Jake and I create our second round of art kits on Wednesday, Aug. 26.

CEC volunteers Pamela Hubbard, Mike Gordon, Jill Ulm, Suzette Donosky, and Amy Bereson helped us assemble the kits that will be distributed to students this week; plus Kasey Nance is designing an infographic that will be included in the kits.

The Art Department is so thankful for your time and generosity. We couldn’t have done it without you and appreciate everything you do for NPA!

Thanks again,

Whitney Garwood & Jake Fischer

post_text:
CEC needs your support for a teacher appreciation event. (Let's make them smile!)

Teaching in 2020 – what a challenge! NPA’s parent volunteer group – the Community Enrichment Committee – doesn’t want social distancing to prevent us from reminding our great teachers and staff how much we appreciate them.

Starting in September, the CEC is launching a weekly “So Grateful 4 U" Drawing.
Each week, two faculty or staff members will be drawn for a $20 gift card to a local restaurant.

To make this happen, we need your support. Our goal is to raise $630.

We recognize that times are tough for many people right now, so it may not be a good time for you to donate. (We totally get it!)

But if you can make a donation, any amount is appreciated.
Here is the link to learn more:
gf.me/u/yuwbtc

Thank you for your support of our efforts!

post_text: Congratulations to Laura Shafer on being among the finalists for Arizona History Teacher of the Year!!
shared_text:
Superintendent Kathy Hoffman
August 24 at 2:11 PM ·

Congratulations to Katherine Reddy, who teaches at Westwood High School at Mesa Public Schools for being recognized by The Gilder Lehrman Institute of American History as Arizona's 2020 History Teacher of the Year. Ms. Reddy is in her eighth year of teaching and is an Arizona State University graduate!

When accepting her award, Ms. Reddy shared, "My hope is that when they walk out of my classroom on the last day of school, each student does so as an open-minded and civically engaged individual ready to negotiate a complex and often divisive world with a more critical, inquisitive, and empathetic mind and with the skills and awareness to navigate and understand diverse perspectives."

https://www.gilderlehrman.org/programs-and-events/national-history-teacher-year

post_text:
DONATE KNITTING ITEMS

Thick, chunky yarn and knitting needles are currently being collected for NPA students & faculty who are busy knitting scarves for the Harry Potter-themed celebration on April 11. Scarves will be tossed to spectators during the Quidditch match between Juniors & Seniors.

The Harry Potter Party began last year as an event to welcome 8th grade students to the high school. It was such a success this year it will be open to the entire NPA community.
What We Need: Chunky yarns in Harry Potter colors – Maroon, Dark Green, Navy, Gold, plus black, grey and white. (Walmart sells a "Super Skein" for $5.) Knitting needles, size 13 or 15.

Please drop off donations at the reception desk of the NPA main building. Thank you!

Thick, chunky yarn and knitting needles are currently being collected for NPA students & faculty who are busy knitting scarves for the Harry Potter-themed celebration on April 11. Scarves will be tossed to spectators during the Quidditch match between Juniors & Seniors.

The Harry Potter Party began last year as an event to welcome 8th grade students to the high school. It was such a success this year it will be open to the entire NPA community.
What We Need: Chunky yarns in Harry Potter colors – Maroon, Dark Green, Navy, Gold, plus black, grey and white. (Walmart sells a "Super Skein" for $5.) Knitting needles, size 13 or 15.

Please drop off donations at the reception desk of the NPA main building. Thank you!

Last week was the last week for the high school winter season, with today the first official day of practice for high school spring sports (sure looks like spring outside today!). Middle school girls basketball finishes out their regular season this week, with the single elimination city championship beginning next week. Please congratulate Will Baldwin, whose middle school JV girl's teams these past two years have accumulated a record of 22 wins and 2 losses (last year’s loss came in the City Championship final)! Will’s team this year has only suffered one loss in the regular season.

Our boy’s high school basketball team may still be in the hunt for the state championship bracket playoffs, but won’t know until Tuesday at noon when the final rankings come out, as the team sits on the bubble.

Students: as we return from break, the faculty felt like you may need some reminders once again in the new semester:
Backpacks are not allowed in classrooms or to be carried around during the day. We have small classrooms and small students.

Cell phones are not to be out during the school day unless specific permission is granted by your classroom teacher. If we see it, we take it.

Hats and hoods are not to be worn indoors. After a warning, they will be taken.

Headphones and earbuds should not be in your ears when walking between classes. If you cannot hear, there is a safety issue at hand.

Please be respectful of our rules in both buildings. The faculty enforces these rules to ensure safety and keep the school focused on academics. They should not have to repeat themselves and tell you these rules multiple times. Thank you!

post_text:
Last Saturday (12/7), 6 of the Chess Team members participated in the Killip Classic. Here are the outcomes.

Open Section (USCF ratings 751 and greater) with 21 participants
1. Osman Werner: 7th grade. Won 3rd Place in the Open section.
2. JJ Adachi: 7th grade. He had a rough day and placed 11th in the Open section.
3. Ryan Funk-Clark: 8th grade. Placed 14th in the Open section. So far this year, he improved his ratings by over 200 points.
U750 Section (USCF ratings between 551 and 750) with 26 participants
1. Liam Wilcox: 7th grade. Finished 18th place out. This was his second tournament. He is making progress.
U500 Section (grades 4-12) with 53 participants
1. Brantson Waites: 9th grade. Placed 7th. This is his second year of chess. He doubled his rating in this tournament.
2. Mason Cunningham: 6th grade. Placed 20th. This was his second tournament. He doubled his rating as well.

Congratulations NPA chess team!!

post_text:
The NPA high school girls soccer team won their third-straight State Championship on Saturday night down in Gilbert by shutting out an excellent Chino Valley team 2-zero. The night before our middle school girls Varsity volleyball team, coached by Deja Moseng won the varsity City Championship, while our Junior Varsity girls won their Consolation Match! The NPA mountain biking team closed out their season with a 7th place finish, just in front of 8th place Flagstaff High School and behind schools with populations in the thousands. Middle school cross country finished out their season at state in Surprise, AZ with some personal best times. And of course there was the Saturday morning Showcase and last night’s high school boys soccer award’s potluck.

Only high school cross country and swim and dive are still alive for fall sports with swim and dive competing at their State Championships on Thursday and Friday and cross country running their Sectional Championships on Friday. Good luck Spartans!

The NPA mountain biking team closed out their season with a 7th place finish, just in front of 8th place Flagstaff High School and behind schools with populations in the thousands. Middle school cross country finished out their season at state in Surprise, AZ with some personal best times. And of course there was the Saturday morning Showcase and last night’s high school boys soccer award’s potluck.

Only high school cross country and swim and dive are still alive for fall sports with swim and dive competing at their State Championships on Thursday and Friday and cross country running their Sectional Championships on Friday. Good luck Spartans!
